The article is a transcript of a briefing by Homeland Security Secretary Napolitano, Assistant to the President for Counterterrorism and Homeland Security Brennan, and Press Secretary Gibbs. They discuss the attempted terrorist attack on Christmas Day and the subsequent review of the watchlisting system. They highlight the failures and shortcomings of the system and make recommendations for corrective action. These include assigning responsibility for investigating high-priority threats, distributing intelligence reports more rapidly, strengthening the analytic process, and improving the criteria for adding individuals to terrorist watchlists. They also discuss the actions taken by the Department of Homeland Security to strengthen screening requirements and deploy additional security measures at airports. The briefing addresses questions regarding the motivation behind terrorist attacks, the role of international cooperation in aviation security, and the need for counter-radicalization efforts.